description: Cultivated Meyer lemon tree being eaten by a katydid.

Large green bush katydid on rose, Long Beach suburbs.

Based on location, it's most likely a Mexican bush katydid (Scudderia mexicana) or fork-tailed bush katydid 
(Scudderia furcata).

But S. mexicana has a shorter body, and this clearly has the elongated body proportions of S. furcata.

She had been hanging upside down from the middle of a web stretched right across the top of a cardboard box that I was about to reach into.  Here she has retreated to a corner of the box, but you can still see that lovely red hourglass on her abdomen.

I had lived in Southern California for 13 years and never saw a black widow.  I was in my final week there, in the process of moving out, when I encountered this one.  I had left this cardboard box, containing cleaning supplies (for a final cleaning once the house was empty) outside on the back porch.
